# Anti-slop

## Purpose
- Eliminate redundancy, dead weight, and generic output.
- Prefer clarity in code over commentary; comments only explain *why*.
- Do not invent APIs, structures, or concepts foreign to the repo.

## Local commands
anti-slop check <path>       # non-destructive inspection
anti-slop apply <path>       # applies safe fixes
anti-slop validate <path>    # validates types, routes, schemas

Flags:
--mode normal | backend | frontend | design
--auto-apply
--dry-run

## Engineering rules (always)

### Backend
- Clean, non-duplicated REST routes.
- Single HTTP client and single DB client (no parallel stacks).
- Handlers <10 lines; logic lives in services.
- Mandatory Zod validation at boundaries.
- Errors have a uniform shape.
- ENV validated at startup.

### Frontend (technical)
- Server Components by default; `use client` only when essential.
- Tailwind without arbitrary values.
- Images include `width`/`height` and lazy-load when appropriate.
- Targets: LCP ≤ 2.5s, INP ≤ 200ms, CLS ≤ 0.1.
- Accessibility: contrast ≥ 4.5 and keyboardable UI.

### Design system (always)
- Colors come from tokens; no hex.
- Spacing, typography, radii, z-index, motion come from tokens.
- Max 1–2 animations per view, only when they serve hierarchy.

### PR / change control
- Destructive changes require a human PR.
- API, DB, auth contracts, or tokens require mandatory review.

## Commit messages (always)
- Use Conventional Commits or include a ticket.
- Message must explain the *why*, not just the *what*.
- If changes contain an AI footprint (markers, comments, patterns), include:
  - `AI-REVIEWED: <ticket|initials>`

Valid:
- feat(api): adds Zod validation to protect /users route
- fix(ui): fixes CLS by adding width/height to images (ABC-142)
- refactor(core): removes duplicated policy evaluation — AI-REVIEWED: JG

Invalid:
- update
- small fix
- minor changes

## Nuclear mode (manual only; never “by default”)
Use only with:
anti-slop purge <path> --mode nuclear --destructive-open-pr

### Principles
- Zero redundancy.
- Zero unnecessary comments.
- Zero wrapper code without semantic value.
- Avoid excessive structural depth (prefer max ~2 nested levels).

### Allowed actions
- Delete duplicated functions and passive wrappers.
- Remove unused imports.
- Flatten structure when it reduces mental overhead.
- Split multi-responsibility functions into single-purpose units.
- Delete “organizer” files that contain no logic.
- Rename generic variables (`data`, `info`, `result`) to semantic names.

### Red flags (remove)
- Syntax comments.
- Commented-out code.
- Redundant try/catch.
- Files that only re-export.
- Empty AI-words (“robust”, “seamless”, etc.).

## Frontend design engineering (applies when the task is UI/UX/styling)

### Activation triggers
Applies when the request includes any of:
- UI, frontend, web, landing, dashboard, page, component
- styling, layout, spacing, colors, fonts, motion
- “beautify”, “polish”, “make it nicer”

### Non-negotiables
- No generic layouts or “template” structure.
- No hard-coded visual values (use tokens).
- Aesthetics must be intentional and explainable.
- Maintain semantic HTML, reading order, contrast, and keyboard navigation.

### Concept hook (required)
- Each new/changed view must have a visible, verifiable "concept hook" with objective verification criteria.
- Choose one directional approach, don't blend randomly. Accepted concept hooks include:
  - diagonal kinetic grid (e.g., staggered card layouts with angled separators)
  - typographic collage layout (e.g., overlapping text elements with varied sizes)
  - noise-texture atmosphere (e.g., subtle grain overlays or geometric patterns)
  - brutalist grid-break fold (e.g., sharp corners with intentional breaks)
- PR description must include: 2-3 line design rationale explaining the chosen concept hook and how it serves the user experience, plus Design Lead sign-off field for pass/fail verification.

### Typography
- Max 2 font families.
- Must be tokenized (`type.family.*`, `type.weight.*`, `type.tracking.*`).
- Use of non-standard fonts (Inter, Roboto, Poppins, Montserrat, Space Grotesk, DM Sans, system-ui) requires a short justification covering legibility, licensing, contrast proof, and product fit rationale.
- All new fonts require license + legibility + contrast proof and usage rationale.

### Color
- Token-only, semantic purpose per color (hierarchy/state/signal).
- Avoid generic SaaS gradient conventions unless explicitly justified for brand/product strategy.
- Adjustments bounded (lighten/darken up to ~±15%).

### Layout & space
- Spacing from tokens; no “padding by habit”.
- Break at least one pattern intentionally (asymmetry, controlled overflow, diagonals, collage, extreme negative space) without breaking a11y.

### Components
- Prefer existing components; extend via composition, don’t mutate bases.
- No wrapper components without visual/behavioral responsibility.
- If using shadcn: composition > modification; no template copying.

### Motion
- Max 1–2 high-impact moments per view.
- No default easing; motion must reinforce hierarchy and rhythm.

### Textures/materials (if used)
- Must be licensed and intentional (grain, geometric noise, paper/dust, etc.).

### Forbidden (auto-fail)
- Generic “hero + 3 columns + CTA” layouts.
- Symmetric centered grids without a stated reason.
- Default parallax and “template” motion.
- UI that looks like a generic kit with a palette swap.

### Delivery checklist (required for UI work)
- Declared aesthetic direction + concept hook
- Complete token mapping (colors/type/space/radii/motion)
- 2–5 lines of visual rationale
- A11y evidence (contrast + keyboard)
- Performance evidence (LCP/INP/CLS targets)
- Confirmation: "No generic elements / no AI patterns"
- Design Engineering approval when the change is visual/brand-defining

### Exceptions
- Only per ticket, with rationale and Design Owner approval (expires in 30 days).